</div>
<div class="thumb tright">
<div class="thumbinner" style="width:302px;"><a href="/wiki/File:Mobile_phone_subscribers_per_100_inhabitants_1997-2007_ITU.png" class="image" title="Mobile phone subscribers per 100 inhabitants growth in developed and developing world between 1997 and 2007"><img alt="" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/19/Mobile_phone_subscribers_per_100_inhabitants_1997-2007_ITU.png/300px-Mobile_phone_subscribers_per_100_inhabitants_1997-2007_ITU.png" width="300" height="267" border="0" class="thumbimage" /></a>
<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Mobile_phone_subscribers_per_100_inhabitants_1997-2007_ITU.png" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
<a href="/wiki/Mobile_phone" title="Mobile phone">Mobile phone</a> subscribers per 100 inhabitants growth in developed and developing world between 1997 and 2007</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>The term <b>digital divide</b> refers to the gap between people with effective access to <a href="/wiki/Digital" title="Digital">digital</a> and <a href="/wiki/Information_technology" title="Information technology">information technology</a> and those with very limited or no access at all. It includes the imbalances in physical access to <a href="/wiki/Technology" title="Technology">technology</a> as well as the imbalances in resources and skills needed to effectively participate as a <a href="/wiki/Digital_citizen" title="Digital citizen">digital citizen</a>. In other words, it is the unequal access by some members of <a href="/wiki/Society" title="Society">society</a> to information and communications technology, and the unequal acquisition of related skills. The digital divide may be classified based on <a href="/wiki/Gender" title="Gender">gender</a>, <a href="/wiki/Income" title="Income">income</a>, and <a href="/wiki/Race" title="Race">race</a> groups, and by locations.<sup id="cite_ref-Rice105_0-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Rice105-0" title=""><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> The term <a href="/wiki/Global_digital_divide" title="Global digital divide">global digital divide</a> refers to differences in technology access between countries or large regions of the world.</p>
